Problem

I am trying to figure out why the hybrid TSIR chain binomial is overshooting the estimates (See poster. If it doesn’t work, just refresh the page.). Let’s step through it starting from the very beginning.

Discrete Latent State TSIR Chain Binomial

Model

_ I didn’t change the parameter names in the code (I will for the paper later… I just want to get over this wall for now and be semi-formal at the same time. So \(\alpha = effprop\), r is repMean,\(\beta = \textrm{exp}(\frac{-R_{0}}{N})\)

The Reed-Frost model is a discrete-time SIR model that assumes recovery one time step after infection. Let \(N\) be the population size, \(I_{1}\) be the initial number of infectives, \(\beta\) be the probability of adequate contact per infective, then the RF model can be written as:

\[ S_{1} = N - I_{1} \\ I_{t} \sim \textrm{Binomial}(\textrm{prob} = 1-(1-\beta)^{I_{t-1}} , \textrm{size}=S_{t-1}) \\ S_{t} = S_{t-1} - I_{t} \]

We modified the RF model as a latent binomial process and added an observation process with reporting probability \(r\) and assumed \(N_{e}\) is from an effective population with an effective proportion \(\alpha\) of the upper limit population size N. The modified RF model can be written as:

\[ N_{e} \sim \textrm{Binomial}(\textrm{prob} = \alpha, \textrm{size}=N) \\ S_{1} = N_{e} - I_{1} \\ I_{t} \sim \textrm{Binomial}(\textrm{prob} = 1-(1-\beta)^{I_{t-1}} , \textrm{size}=S_{t-1}) \\ Obs_{t} \sim \textrm{Binomial}(\textrm{prob}=r,\textrm{size}=I_{t}) \\ S_{t} = S_{t-1} - I_{t} \]

Jags Discrete Latent State Model Results

Using the same parameters as the models in the poster, here are the plots/chains for the discrete latent state chain binomial. Note I used stronger priors for the poster and uninformative priors Beta(1,1) for \(\alpha\) and \(r\). I also used the true parameters as the initial starting point to see if we can even estimate the parameters given we have a good starting point.

Parameters

  • \(R_{0} = 2\)
  • \(\beta = 0.7 , \textrm{(effective proportion of population)}\)
  • \(r = 0.4 , \textrm{(reporting mean/probability)}\)

Hybrid model

The orginal idea of hybridization was to improve the mixing for r with some sort of Scaling trick/ cliff. We later realized we can take this further and use a more powerful MCMC algorithm (Hamiltonian Monte Carlo). For now, let’s try to figure out the problem in JAGS

First we want to change the discrete latent process to continuous by setting the first and second moment (moment-matching (MM)) of the binomial distribution to a continuous distribution (ie. gamma in this case) and observation process to a poisson process (more detail on why possion).

… skip all the moment-matching algebra …

We can rewrite the model (todo: reference equation/system of equations?) as:

\[ N_{e} \sim \textrm{Binomial}(\alpha,N) \\ S_{1} = N_{e} - I_{1} \\ I_{t} \sim \textrm{Gamma}(\textrm{shape} = \textrm{prob}\times S_{t-1} \times \textrm{rate}, \textrm{rate}= \frac{1}{1-\textrm{prob}}) \\ Obs_{t} \sim \textrm{Poisson}(\textrm{mean}=r \times I_{t}) \\ S_{t} = S_{t-1} - I_{t} \]
